[[File:Isaiah-Emmanuel-Morter-status-Belize-City.jpg|thumb|Morter's statue near the St John's Cathedral in Belize City]]
'''Isaiah Emmanuel Morter''' (sometimes spelled '''Isiah''') (1860 &ndash; 7 April 1924) was born in 1860 in the Freetown district of [[Belize]]. He was of [[Igbo people|Igbo]] descent (some say his parents were [[Ashanti people|Ashanti]] royalty)<ref>Peter David Ashdown, ''Garveyism in Belize'', 1990, p. 22.</ref> coming from a line of slaves brought to America from Nigeria. [[Marcus Garvey]] wrote that "[[Morter]] grew up fighting the oppositions and difficulties generally surrounding one born to his condition, until he lifted himself to the highest pinnacle of service to his race and to his country."<ref>Garvey, Marcus, "A tribute to the late Sir Isaiah Morter", ''Philosophy and opinions of March Garvey'', vol. 2, [[Amy Jacques Garvey]], 1977, p. 90.</ref> 

By planting and growing bananas and coconuts, Morter built a fortune and is widely regarded as Belize's first coloured [[millionaire]]. His nicknames included "the Coconut King" and "Guinea Sigar"<ref>''The Marcus Garvey and Universal Negro Improvement Association Papers'', Volume ... by [[Robert A. Hill (Jamaican historian)|Robert A. Hill]], John Dixon, Mariela Haro Rodriguez, Anthony Yuen, 2011, p. 639.</ref> and he owned [[Caye Chapel]]<ref>{{cite web|author=vicky<!-- #title --> |url=http://amandala.com.bz/news/ashcroft-sells-caye-chapel-us30-mil/ |title=Ashcroft sells Caye Chapel for US$30 mil &#124; Amandala Newspaper |publisher=Amandala.com.bz |date=2013-08-30 |accessdate=2014-07-11}}</ref> and other plantations. For his achievements he was honoured with the award of Knight Commander of Distinguished Service Order of Ethiopia.<ref name="belizemusicworld1">{{cite web|url=http://www.belizemusicworld.com/Isiah-Emmanuel-Morter.html |title=Sie-Isaiah-Emmanuel-Morter |publisher=Belizemusicworld.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-11}}</ref> He was also a strong supporter of Marcus Garvey's [[Universal Negro Improvement Association and African Communities League|Universal Negro Improvement Association]].<ref name="belizemusicworld1"/>

Morter died on 7 April 1924. 

A statue of Morter can be found at the end of Albert Street, near St. John's Cathedral , in Belize City. He is not widely known today by the public in Belize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=17331 |title=Few Remember Old Isiah Morter |publisher=7 News Belize |date=2010-07-12 |accessdate=2014-07-11}}</ref>

