{{Infobox person | name = Kyosen Ōhashi | native_name = 大橋 巨泉 | native_name_lang = ja | image = Oohashi Kyosen.jpg | alt = | caption = Ōhashi in 1966 | birth_name = 大橋 克巳 (Ōhashi Katsumi) | birth_date = {{Birth date|1934|03|22}} | birth_place = [[Sumida, Tokyo|Sumida]], [[Tokyo]], Japan | death_date = {{Death date and age|2016|07|12|1934|03|22}} | death_place = | nationality = Japanese | other_names = | occupation = Television host and writer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | website = }} {{nihongo|'''Kyosen Ōhashi'''|大橋 巨泉|Ōhashi Kyosen|extra=March 22, 1934 – July 12, 2016}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.co.jp/pickup/6208265|title=大橋巨泉さん死去 82歳 {{!}} 2016年7月20日(水) - Yahoo!ニュース|language=ja-JP|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref> was a Japanese television host and writer. He also served briefly as a member of the [[Japanese House of Councillors|House of Councillors]] in the [[Diet of Japan]]. His real name was Ōhashi Katsumi (大橋 克巳).<ref>[http://secondlife.yahoo.co.jp/life/master/profile/b101okyos.html profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205042553/http://secondlife.yahoo.co.jp/life/master/profile/b101okyos.html |date=2007-02-05 }}</ref>
Born in [[Sumida, Tokyo]], he grew up in [[Chiba prefecture]] and dropped out of the [[Waseda University]]. Declaring "semi-retirement", he then spent most of his time outside Japan, particularly in [[Canada]] during the summer, as well as in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] during the winter in the northern hemisphere, in which he ran his "OK Gift Shop" (OK stands for '''O'''hashi '''K'''yosen).
When he resigned in the House of Councillors, Ōhashi was succeeded by [[Marutei Tsurunen]], the first European-descended and openly [[foreign-born Japanese]] person to serve in the Diet.
