[[File:William_Cotts.jpg|thumb|right|Sir William Cotts]]

'''Sir William Dingwall Mitchell Cotts, 1st Baronet''', [[KBE]] (15 July 1871 – 20 January 1932) was a Scottish businessman and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.

==Personal life and career==

Cotts was born at [[Sanquhar]] in [[Scotland]], the son of William Cotts. He was educated privately and at [[Wallace Hall Academy]]. In 1901, he married Agnes Sloane who was also from Sanquhar and they had two sons and a daughter.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref> Cotts obtained his early business training in [[Dumfries]] and [[London]] and went in 1895 to South Africa, where he developed important business interests, realising the potential of the [[Colony of Natal|Natal]] coalfields and the transport and other infrastructure that was needed to support the coal and gold mining industries.<ref>The Times, 22 January 1932 p12</ref> He also had business interests in Britain and was sometime head of Mitchell, Cotts& Co. of London. The company traded as general merchants, owned collieries and steamships.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref>

==Political and public life==

Cotts contested the [[Na h-Eileanan an Iar (UK Parliament constituency)|Western Isles]] constituency at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1918|1918 general election]] as a [[Coalition government 1916-1922|Coalition Liberal]] but narrowly failed to take the seat which was won by an [[H H Asquith|Independent Liberal]], Dr [[Donald Murray (Scottish politician)|Donald Murray]] with a majority of 390 votes. Cotts fought Murray for the seat again in [[United Kingdom general election, 1922|1922]] standing as a [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1922)|National Liberal]], i.e. a supporter of the [[David Lloyd George]]. This time he won, with a majority of 939. He served as [[Member of Parliament (UK)|MP]] until [[United Kingdom general election, 1923|1923]] but did contest any further Parliamentary elections.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results 1918-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p629, OUP, 2007</ref>

Cotts was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for the [[County of London]] and was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) in 1919 for services to recruiting.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31422 |date=27 June 1919 |page=8090}}</ref><ref>The Times, 22 January 1932 p12</ref> He served on the Council of [[Westfield College]], [[University of London]] Homes for Little Boys.  He was created a [[baronet]] in 1921.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32558 |date=23 December 1921 |page=10486}}</ref><ref>The Times, 18 November 1922</ref>

==Death and heir==

Cotts died suddenly at the age of 60 while travelling to [[Wales]] for medical treatment. He was succeeded in the [[Cotts baronets|Cotts baronetcy]] by his son William.<ref>The Times, 22 January 1932 p12</ref> [[Campbell Cotts|Sir William Campbell Mitchell-Cotts]] (1902–1964), a [[barrister]] contested the [[Forest of Dean (UK Parliament constituency)|Forest of Dean]] constituency at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1929|1929 general election]] as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]. Mitchell-Cotts was in 1928 unpaid private secretary to [[Tory]] politician [[Duff Cooper]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP, 2007</ref>

